    "Our goal in noisy label learning is to find a loss function L that minimizes the discrepancy between the risks of f * (•) and f * (•).",
    "B. Label Noise ModelingTo model the label noise, we follows convention and formulates the noisy label ŷ as (y is the ground-truth label):ŷ = y with probability (1 -η y), j, j ∈ [k], j ̸ = y with probability η yj,(1)where η yj denotes the probability that true label y is corrupted into label j, and η y = j̸ =y η yj denotes the noise rate of label y.",
    "This model follows the class-dependent label noise assumption, where the noise transition probability depends on the sample class or target class.",
    "Additionally, under this classdependent assumption, we can distinguish two specific types of label noise: symmetric and asymmetric.For symmetric label noise [41], the corruption rate is uniform, meaningη ij = ηi K-1, ∀j ̸ = y and η i = η, ∀i ∈ [k],where the whole modeling is decided by a constant η.",
    "In this case, each label has an equal chance of being corrupted into any other label.For asymmetric label noise [14], [42], the noise rate η ij depends on both the true label i and the corrupted label j."
  ],
